@flexiarg collaboration-coherence/weak-tie-conflation
@title Be Honest About Tie Strength; Match Asks to Tie Type
@keywords weak-ties, strong-ties, tie-strength, granovetter, peer-illusion, audience-vs-team
@audience peer-learning facilitators, project conveners, network conveners
@tone reflective
@style pattern
@references [peeragogy/carrying-capacity peeragogy/newcomer collaboration-coherence/messy-with-lurkers]

! conclusion: Weak ties and strong ties serve different functions; both are useful, neither is "better."  The failure mode is self-deception about which kind of tie a relationship actually is — calling a weak-tie audience "peers," calling a strong-tie team "the network," or asking weak-tie services from strong-tie relationships and vice-versa.  The pattern is to name the actual ties honestly, match asks to tie type, and convert ties deliberately when the project needs the conversion.
  + context: Peer-learning projects often blur the distinction.  Participants share a forum, watch each other's video calls, read each other's posts — and conclude they are "peers" in a strong sense.  In practice, most such ties are weak: useful for diverse information, weak for instrumental support.  Strong ties are reciprocal, demand-bearing, sustained by repeated context-rich interaction.  Weak ties bring more diverse knowledge but cannot be asked for the favours strong ties can.  The handbook's source note catches it: "I'm failing to be a good peeragogue... should be responsible not only for your own learning but for your peers' learning"; if no one is taking responsibility for anyone else's learning, the relationship is a weak-tie audience, not a peer-tie team.  Self-deception about which kind of tie is in play converts to disappointment when the wrong kind of ask is made.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: aspirational tie-strength ↔ actual tie-strength.
    Real: aspirations to peer-like reciprocity are part of what brings a community together.  Naming actual tie-strength can feel like puncturing the aspiration.  But asks calibrated to aspiration rather than reality reliably fail and corrode trust.
    Irreducible: a tie cannot simultaneously be cheaply joinable (audience-shaped) and reciprocally demand-bearing (team-shaped).  Each tie is one or the other at any moment, and the conversion between them is deliberate work.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever someone introduces "the community" or "the network" without distinguishing layers, whenever a request flies through a forum that is structured as audience but treated as team, and whenever a member feels betrayed because the implicit ask wasn't met.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Honest naming: in the project's self-description, distinguish layers: audience (read-only, weak ties), participants (occasional, weak-to-medium), contributors (engaged, medium-to-strong), team (committed, strong, reciprocal).  Use the names consistently.
    (2) Match ask to tie: information and weak-signal asks (recommendations, tool suggestions, perspective) belong on weak-tie surfaces; instrumental asks (review my draft, debug with me, cover my workload) belong on strong-tie surfaces.  Posting strong-tie asks to weak-tie audiences gets random uptake at best.
    (3) Deliberate conversion: weak ties become strong through *repeated context-rich interaction* — pair work, named co-facilitation, sustained back-and-forth.  Project design that makes conversion easy (named pairings, mentorship pairs, working groups) extends the strong-tie layer over time.
    (4) Don't grandfather aspiration: when the project's self-description outpaces the actual tie strength, revise the self-description rather than scolding the participants.  The community is the data; the labels should match.
    (5) Pair with carrying-capacity: strong ties cost more per relationship than weak ties; respecting the carrying capacity of strong-tie holders is part of honest tie-management.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: project self-description distinguishes audience / participants / team layers; asks are routed by tie-type; named transitions exist between layers.  Failing when: "peers" is the only label, asks are made indiscriminately, or members feel betrayed because the implicit relationship was stronger than the actual one.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Peer-illusion: the project calls everyone a "peer" while actual ties are mostly audience-shaped; instrumental asks fail and the project reads the failure as participation pathology.
    - Co-consumer claim: members report being "co-learners" when the actual relationship is co-watching the same content (a 4th-wall audience, in the source's framing).
    - Forum-as-team: an audience forum is treated as a team channel; significant decisions are posted to it and the random uptake is read as community endorsement.
    - Strong-tie ghosting: someone asks a strong-tie favour through a weak-tie surface, gets no response, and concludes the community has failed them — when the actual issue is the wrong surface.
    - Conversion-by-osmosis fantasy: the project assumes weak ties will become strong through proximity alone, without the deliberate context-rich interaction that conversion actually requires.
